President Yoon Suk Yeol of the Republic of Korea (ROK) welcomes President Joseph R. Biden of the United States to South Korea, marking an early meeting in a ROK President's term. The alliance between the ROK and the U.S. continues to evolve and expand, reflecting their roles as global leaders in democracy, economy, and technology. Both leaders are unified in their determination to strengthen political, economic, security, and people-to-people ties. They reaffirm their commitment to the defense of the ROK and the combined defense posture under the ROK-U.S. Mutual Defense Treaty. They also agree to reactivate the high-level Extended Deterrence Strategy and Consultation Group and discuss expanding military exercises on the Korean Peninsula. The two Presidents share the goal of denuclearizing the Korean Peninsula and urge the DPRK to abandon its weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missile programs. They also express concern over the human rights situation in the DPRK and pledge to provide humanitarian aid. In terms of economic and technology partnership, they pledge to deepen cooperation on critical and emerging technologies, cyber security, economic and energy security, and global supply chains. They also commit to addressing climate change and the COVID-19 pandemic, as well as opposing activities that threaten the rules-based international order, such as Russia's aggression against Ukraine. The two leaders emphasize the importance of a free and open Indo-Pacific, ASEAN centrality, and promoting human rights globally. They recognize the maturing of the ROK-U.S. alliance into a deep and comprehensive strategic relationship. President Biden invites President Yoon to visit Washington in the future.